    <discussion>Western Native Americans (Bella Colla, Cowlitz, Kwakiutl, Okanagan, Quinault,
        Salishan, Shuswap, and Thompson) used Veratrum viride var. eschscholzianum as an analgesic,
        antirheumatic, emetic, laxative, and poison, as well as a cold, blood, heart, orthopedic,
        and skin aid (D. E. Moerman 1986). Native Americans from northern British Columbia and the
        Yukon Territory consumed young plants as herbage (A. E. Porsild 1951; G. A. Mulligan and D.
        B. Munro 1987).</discussion>
